  <div class="section-header">
    <div class="section-tag" style="--accent:#0d9e7e">Module 03</div>
    <h2 class="section-title">MPD & <span style="color:var(--accent3)">MySQL</span></h2>
    <p class="section-intro">Le Modèle Physique des Données traduit le MLD dans le langage d'un SGBD précis : ici MySQL. On définit les types, les contraintes, et on écrit le SQL.</p>
  </div>

  <!-- CONVENTIONS -->
  <div class="card">
    <div class="card-title">📏 Conventions MySQL</div>
    <div class="concept-grid">
      <div class="concept-card" style="--c:#00d4aa">
        <h4>Nommage</h4>
        <p>Tout en <strong>minuscules</strong>, alphabet anglais, <strong>underscores</strong> à la place des espaces. Max 20 caractères (convention Oracle).</p>
      </div>
      <div class="concept-card" style="--c:#6c63ff">
        <h4>Casse</h4>
        <p>MySQL est <strong>sensible à la casse</strong> : <code>student</code> ≠ <code>Student</code>. Toujours utiliser les minuscules.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="concept-card" style="--c:#ffa94d">
        <h4>Préfixage</h4>
        <p>Préfixer les attributs par un abrégé du nom de table : <code>std_name</code> (student), <code>unv_name</code> (university).</p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="callout callout-info">
      <span class="callout-icon">💡</span>
      <div>Le préfixage permet d'identifier immédiatement les <strong>clés étrangères</strong> dans les requêtes multi-tables. <code>unv_name</code> dans student → c'est une FK vers university.</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- TYPES DE DONNÉES -->
  <div class="card">
    <div class="card-title">🗃️ Les Types de Données MySQL</div>
    <div class="types-grid">
      <div class="type-card" style="--tc:#6c63ff">
        <div class="type-name">VARCHAR(n)</div>
        <div class="type-desc">Chaîne de caractères de longueur variable. n = nombre max de caractères.</div>
        <div class="type-example">std_name VARCHAR(30)</div>
      </div>
      <div class="type-card" style="--tc:#ff6b9d">
        <div class="type-name">ENUM('a','b',...)</div>
        <div class="type-desc">Liste prédéfinie de valeurs autorisées.</div>
        <div class="type-example">size ENUM('S','M','L')</div>
      </div>
      <div class="type-card" style="--tc:#ffa94d">
        <div class="type-name">INT / INTEGER</div>
        <div class="type-desc">Entier standard. Plage : -2 147 483 648 à 2 147 483 647.</div>
        <div class="type-example">std_id INT</div>
      </div>
      <div class="type-card" style="--tc:#00d4aa">
        <div class="type-name">TINYINT</div>
        <div class="type-desc">Petit entier : -128 à 127. Utile pour les âges, notes…</div>
        <div class="type-example">note TINYINT</div>
      </div>
      <div class="type-card" style="--tc:#6c63ff">
        <div class="type-name">DECIMAL(p,s)</div>
        <div class="type-desc">Nombre exact. p = précision totale, s = chiffres après virgule.</div>
        <div class="type-example">prix DECIMAL(10,2)</div>
      </div>
      <div class="type-card" style="--tc:#ff6b9d">
        <div class="type-name">DATE / DATETIME</div>
        <div class="type-desc">Date seule ou date+heure.</div>
        <div class="type-example">date_debut DATE</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- SQL DE BASE -->
  <div class="card">
    <div class="card-title">⌨️ Les Commandes SQL Essentielles</div>

    <p style="font-size:0.85rem;color:var(--muted);margin-bottom:1rem">Voici la structure complète pour créer et peupler une base. L'ordre est crucial !</p>

    <div class="code-block" style="margin-bottom:1.2rem">
      <div class="code-label">CREATE DATABASE</div>
<span class="kw">CREATE DATABASE</span> education<span class="str">;</span>
    </div>

    <div class="code-block" style="margin-bottom:1.2rem">
      <div class="code-label">CREATE TABLE</div>
<span class="kw">CREATE TABLE</span> university(
  unv_name <span class="type">VARCHAR</span>(50) <span class="fn">NOT NULL PRIMARY KEY</span>,
  unv_country <span class="type">VARCHAR</span>(20) <span class="fn">NOT NULL</span>,
  unv_address <span class="type">VARCHAR</span>(90) <span class="fn">NOT NULL</span>
)<span class="str">;</span>

<span class="kw">CREATE TABLE</span> student(
  std_id <span class="type">INT</span> <span class="fn">NOT NULL PRIMARY KEY</span>,
  unv_name <span class="type">VARCHAR</span>(50),
  std_name <span class="type">VARCHAR</span>(30) <span class="fn">NOT NULL</span>,
  std_nationality <span class="type">VARCHAR</span>(20) <span class="fn">NOT NULL</span>,
  <span class="fn">FOREIGN KEY</span> (unv_name) <span class="fn">REFERENCES</span> university(unv_name)
)<span class="str">;</span>
    </div>

    <div class="callout callout-warning">
      <span class="callout-icon">⚠️</span>
      <div><strong>Ordre de création !</strong> Toujours créer la table "parent" (university) AVANT la table "enfant" (student) qui la référence. Sinon : erreur de FK.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="code-block" style="margin-bottom:1.2rem">
      <div class="code-label">INSERT INTO</div>
<span class="kw">INSERT INTO</span> university <span class="kw">VALUES</span>
  (<span class="str">'UTT'</span>, <span class="str">'France'</span>, <span class="str">'Troyes'</span>),
  (<span class="str">'PSB'</span>, <span class="str">'France'</span>, <span class="str">'Paris'</span>)<span class="str">;</span>

<span class="kw">INSERT INTO</span> student <span class="kw">VALUES</span>
  (<span class="num">123</span>, <span class="str">'UTT'</span>, <span class="str">'Alexander'</span>, <span class="str">'American'</span>),
  (<span class="num">345</span>, <span class="str">'PSB'</span>, <span class="str">'Marie'</span>, <span class="str">'French'</span>)<span class="str">;</span>
    </div>

    <div class="code-block" style="margin-bottom:1.2rem">
      <div class="code-label">UPDATE</div>
<span class="kw">UPDATE</span> university
<span class="kw">SET</span> unv_address = <span class="str">'San Francisco'</span>
<span class="kw">WHERE</span> unv_name = <span class="str">'Stanford'</span><span class="str">;</span>
    </div>

    <div class="code-block">
      <div class="code-label">ALTER TABLE</div>
<span class="kw">ALTER TABLE</span> student
<span class="kw">ADD</span> std_age <span class="type">INTEGER</span><span class="str">;</span>
    </div>
  </div>

